      {
        "id": 3112864,
        "name": "Mark Golodetz",
        "username": "Mark_Golodetz",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/mark_golodetz/{size}/76850_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-02-27T23:43:31.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Don\u2019t get me wrong. This is not a 100 point wine. It did not make time stand still not could it have been confused with a great First Growth. However it did beat the hell out of a sad 1970 Lafite which I had last year.</p>\n<p>But this is a 50 plus year Cru Bourgeois, and I only bought ten bottles because the color and fills were good and they were dirt cheap. $225 for all ten. And it came from this incredible cellar that has been defying the odds and producing great wines from the most unlikely estates.</p>\n<p>I opened the first bottle tonight. A little worried, some very volatile aromas were coming off it as I decanted it. They soon blew away, and I got fruit, and also a strong undercurrent of ferrous. The wine is fully mature, and a few other bits of pieces of flavor added to the complexity mostly licorice and spice. The finish is medium, and nicely layered 92/93.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-04T02:35:21.013Z",
